<div id=3D"modular-arithmetic-as-remainders" class=3D"anchor skill-heading =
collapsed" data-controller=3D"app/wiki:expandOrCollapse" data-controller-in=
ited=3D"true">
    <header class=3D"section-header">
        <span class=3D"css-sprite-chevrons chevron"></span>
        <h2>Modular Arithmetic as Remainders</h2>

       =20
    </header>
</div>

<div class=3D"section collapsed" id=3D"section-modular-arithmetic-as-remain=
ders"><div class=3D"section-container">

<p>The easiest way to understand modular arithmetic is to think of it as fi=
nding the remainder of a number upon division by another number. For exampl=
e, since both 15 and -9 leave the same remainder 3 when divided by 12, we s=
ay that</p>

<p>\[15 \equiv -9\pmod{12}.\]</p>

<p>This allows us to have a simple way of doing modular arithmetic: first p=
erform the usual arithmetic, and then find the remainder. For example, to f=
ind \(123 + 321 \pmod{11}\), we can take</p>

<p>\[123 + 321 =3D 444\]</p>

<p>and divide it by 11, which gives us</p>

<p>\[123 + 321 \equiv 4\pmod{11}.\]</p>

<p>However, this could get messy when the numbers get larger. One approach =
that we could take is to first find the remainders of 123 and 321 when divi=
ded by 11 (the remainders are both 2), perform the usual arithmetic, and fi=
nd the remainder again. In this example, since \(123 \equiv 2\pmod{11}\) an=
d \(321 \equiv 2\pmod{11}\), we can conclude that</p>

<p>\[\begin{aligned}
123 + 321  &amp; \equiv 2+2 &amp; \pmod{11} \\
 &amp; \equiv 4 &amp; \pmod{11}. \end{aligned}\]</p>

</div>
</div>

<div id=3D"congruence" class=3D"anchor skill-heading collapsed" data-contro=
ller=3D"app/wiki:expandOrCollapse" data-controller-inited=3D"true">
    <header class=3D"section-header">
        <span class=3D"css-sprite-chevrons chevron"></span>
        <h2>Congruence</h2>

       =20
    </header>
</div>

<div class=3D"section collapsed" id=3D"section-congruence"><div class=3D"se=
ction-container">

<p>For a positive integer \(n\), the integers \(a\) and \(b\) are congruent=
 \( \bmod\ n\) if their remainders when divided by \(n\) are the same.</p>

<blockquote class=3D"example"><p>
\[52 \equiv 24\pmod 7\]</p>

<p>As we can see above, 52 and 24 are congruent (mod 7) because \(52\pmod 7=
 =3D 3\) and \(24\pmod 7 =3D 3.\)</p>

<p>Note that \(=3D\) is different from \(\equiv.\)
</p><!-- end-example --></blockquote>

<p>Another way of defining this is that integers \(a\) and \(b\) are congru=
ent \( \bmod\ n\) if their difference \((a - b)\) is an integer multiple of=
 \(n\), that is, if \(\frac{a-b}{n}\) has a remainder of 0.</p>

<blockquote class=3D"example"><p>
\[36 \equiv 10\pmod{13}\]</p>

<p>36 and 10 are said to be congruent (mod 13) because their difference \(3=
6 - 10 =3D 26\) is an integer multiple of \(n=3D13\), that is, \(26 =3D 2\t=
imes 13.\)
</p><!-- end-example --></blockquote>

</div>
</div>

<div id=3D"modular-arithmetic-addition" class=3D"anchor skill-heading colla=
psed" data-controller=3D"app/wiki:expandOrCollapse" data-controller-inited=
=3D"true">
    <header class=3D"section-header">
        <span class=3D"css-sprite-chevrons chevron"></span>
        <h2>Addition</h2>

       =20
    </header>
</div>

<div class=3D"section collapsed" id=3D"section-modular-arithmetic-addition"=
><div class=3D"section-container">

<blockquote>
  <p><strong>Properties of addition in modular arithmetic:</strong></p>
 =20
  <ol>
  <li>If \(a+b =3D c\), then \(a\pmod N+b\pmod N \equiv c \pmod N.\)</li>
  <li>If \(a\equiv b\pmod N\), then \(a+k \equiv b+k \pmod N\) for any inte=
ger \(k.\)   </li>
  <li>If \(a\equiv b\pmod N\) and \(c\equiv d\pmod N\), then \(a+c \equiv b=
+d \pmod N.\)   </li>
  <li>If \(a \equiv b\pmod N\), then \(-a \equiv -b\pmod N.\)</li>
  </ol>
</blockquote>

<blockquote class=3D"example"><p>
It is currently 7:00 PM. What time (in AM or PM) will it be in 1000 hours?<=
/p>

<hr>

<p>Time "repeats" every 24 hours, so we work modulo 24. Since</p>

<p>\[1000 \equiv 16 + (24\times 41) \equiv 16 \pmod{24},\]</p>

<p>the time in 1000 hours is equivalent to the time in 16 hours. Therefore,=
 it will be 11:00 AM in 1000 hours. \(_\square\)
</p><!-- end-example --></blockquote>

<blockquote class=3D"example"><p>
Find the sum of 31 and 148 in modulo 24.</p>

<hr>

<p><strong>Solution 1:</strong> <br>
31 in modulo 24 is equivalent to 7. If we use the first modular addition ru=
le stated in this wiki, we find that \(31 + 148 \equiv 7 + 148 \equiv 155\p=
mod{24}\). 155 in modulo 24 is 11.  \(_ \square\)</p>

<p><strong>Solution 2:</strong> <br>
 As stated previously, 31 in modulo 24 is 7. Instead of using the first rul=
e, we'll use the second rule. 148 is 4 in modulo 24. So now, all we need to=
 find is 7+4, which is \(11\).  \(_ \square\)</p>

<!-- end-example --></blockquote>

<blockquote class=3D"example">

<h3>Find the remainder when \(123 + 234+ 32+ 56+ 22 + 12 + 78\) is divided =
by \(3.\)</h3>

<hr>

<p>We know that \(123 \equiv 0 \pmod{3}\), \(234 \equiv 0 \pmod{3}\), \(32 =
\equiv 2 \pmod{3}\), \(56 \equiv 2 \pmod{3}\), \(22 \equiv 1 \pmod{3}\), \(=
12 \equiv 0 \pmod{3}\), and \(78 \equiv 0 \pmod{3}\). From  property 3, we =
have</p>

<p>\[123 + 234+ 32+ 56+ 22 + 12 + 78 \equiv 0+0+2+2+1+0+0 \equiv 5 \pmod{3}=
. \]</p>

<p>Since \(5\) has a remainder of \(2\) when divided by \(3\), so does \(12=
3 + 234+ 32+ 56+ 22 + 12 + 78,\) and thus the answer is \(2\). \(_\square\)=
</p>

<!-- end-example --></blockquote>

</div>
</div>

<div id=3D"modular-arithmetic-multiplication" class=3D"anchor skill-heading=
 collapsed" data-controller=3D"app/wiki:expandOrCollapse" data-controller-i=
nited=3D"true">
    <header class=3D"section-header">
        <span class=3D"css-sprite-chevrons chevron"></span>
        <h2>Multiplication</h2>

       =20
    </header>
</div>

<div class=3D"section collapsed" id=3D"section-modular-arithmetic-multiplic=
ation"><div class=3D"section-container">

<p>Modular multiplication appears in many fields of mathematics and has man=
y far-ranging applications, including cryptography, computer science, and c=
omputer algebra.   </p>

<blockquote>
  <p><strong>Properties of multiplication in modular arithmetic</strong>:</=
p>
 =20
  <ol>
  <li>If \( a \cdot b =3D c\), then \( a\pmod N\cdot b\pmod N \equiv c \pmo=
d{N}\).</li>
  <li>If \( a \equiv b \pmod{N}\), then \( ka \equiv kb \pmod{N}\) for any =
integer \( k\).</li>
  <li>If \( a \equiv b \pmod{N}\) and \(c \equiv d \pmod{N}\), then \( ac \=
equiv bd \pmod{N}\).</li>
  </ol>
</blockquote>

<blockquote class=3D"example"><p>
What is \( (8 \times 16) \pmod{7}?\)</p>

<hr>

<p>Since \(8 \equiv 1 \pmod{7}\) and \(16 \equiv 2 \pmod{7}\),  we have</p>

<p>\[ (8 \times 16)  \equiv (1 \times 2) \equiv 2 \pmod{7} .\ _\square \]
</p><!-- end-example --></blockquote>

<blockquote class=3D"example"><p>
Find the remainder when \(124 \cdot 134 \cdot 23 \cdot 49 \cdot 235 \cdot 1=
3\) is divided by \(3\).</p>

<hr>

<p>We did a similar problem above, where the signs were all \( + \) instead=
 of \( \times \). In that case, manually adding the numbers up wouldn't tak=
e that much time, though the modular arithmetic solution was faster. </p>

<p>In this example, multiplying the numbers would be very tedious. Instead,=
 we use property 3 repeatedly. We know that \(124 \equiv 1\), \(134 \equiv =
2\), \(23 \equiv 2\), \(49 \equiv 1\), \(235 \equiv 1\), and \(13 \equiv 1\=
). Therefore, </p>

<p>\[124 \cdot 134 \cdot 23 \cdot 49 \cdot 235 \cdot 13 \equiv 1 \cdot 2 \c=
dot 2 \cdot 1 \cdot 1 \cdot 1 \equiv 4 \equiv 1 \pmod{3}, \]</p>

<p>implying the product, upon division by \(3,\) leaves a remainder of \(1.=
\) \(_\square\)
</p><!-- end-example --></blockquote>

<blockquote class=3D"example"><p>
Prove property 3 of multiplication in modular arithmetic as stated below:</=
p>

<p>If \( a \equiv b \pmod{N} \) and \(c \equiv d \pmod{N}\), then \(ac \equ=
iv bd \pmod{N}\).</p>

<hr>

<p>By the definition of equivalence, \(a -b\) is a multiple of \(N\) and \(=
c-d\) is a multiple of \(N.\) That is,</p>

<p>\[ a-b =3D k_1N, \quad c-d =3D k_2N\]</p>

<p>for constants \(k_1\) and \(k_2\).  Then </p>

<p>\[ \begin{align}
ac - bd &amp;=3D ac - bd +  bc - bc\\
&amp; =3D c(a-b) + b(c-d)\\
&amp; =3D c (k_1 N ) + b (k_2N)\\
&amp; =3D (ck_1 + bk_2) N.
\end{align}\]</p>

<p>This implies \( ac - bd \) is a multiple of \(N\) and therefore \(ac - b=
d \equiv 0 \pmod{N}\), or \(ac \equiv bd \pmod{N}\). \(_\square\)
<!-- end-example --></p></blockquote> <p></p>

