<div id=3D"modular-arithmetic-exponentiation" class=3D"anchor skill-heading=
 collapsed" data-controller=3D"app/wiki:expandOrCollapse" data-controller-i=
nited=3D"true">
    <header class=3D"section-header">
        <span class=3D"css-sprite-chevrons chevron"></span>
        <h2>Exponentiation</h2>

       =20
    </header>
</div>

<div class=3D"section collapsed" id=3D"section-modular-arithmetic-exponenti=
ation"><div class=3D"section-container">

<p>Since exponentiation is repeated multiplication, we have the following:<=
/p>

<blockquote>
  <p><strong>Property of Exponentiation in Modular Arithmetic:</strong></p>
 =20
  <p>If \( a\equiv b\pmod{N}\), then \(a^k \equiv b^k \pmod{N}\) for any po=
sitive integer \(k\).</p>
</blockquote>

<blockquote class=3D"proof"><p>
We can write \(a\) in the form of \(a =3D Np + b\), where \(p\) is some int=
eger. Then we have</p>

<p>\[a^{k} =3D (Np + b)^{k} =3D \sum_{i =3D 0}^{k}\binom{k}{i}(Np)^{k-i}b^{=
i}.\]</p>

<p>Now notice how all the terms of this sum are multiples of \(N\), except =
the last when \(i =3D k\). Hence</p>

<p>\[a^{k} \equiv 0 + 0 + \cdots + 0 + b^{k} =3D b^{k} \pmod{N}.\ _\square\=
]=20
</p><!-- end-proof --></blockquote>

<blockquote class=3D"example"><p>
What is \(3^{16} \pmod{4}?\)</p>

<hr>

<p>We observe that </p>

<p>\[3^2 \equiv 9 \equiv 1 \pmod{4}.\]</p>

<p>Then by the property of exponentiation, we have</p>

<p>\[\begin{align}
3^{16} \pmod{4}=20
&amp;\equiv \big(3^2\big)^8 \pmod{4} \\
&amp;\equiv (1)^8 \pmod{4} \\
&amp;\equiv 1 \pmod{4}. \ _\square
\end{align}\]
</p><!-- end-example --></blockquote>

<p>In the above example, we do not need to find the exact value of \( 3 ^ {=
16} \), which is very large</p>

<blockquote class=3D"example"><p>
What is the last digit of \( 17^{17}?\)</p>

<hr>

<p>The last digit of a number is equivalent to the number taken modulo 10. =
 Working modulo 10, we have</p>

<p>\[\begin{array} { l l l l }
17^{17} &amp; \equiv 7^{17}  &amp; \equiv \big(7^2\big)^8 \cdot 7 &amp; \pm=
od{10}\\
&amp;  \equiv (49)^8 \cdot 7 &amp; \equiv 9^8 \cdot 7 &amp; \pmod{10} \\
&amp;    \equiv \big(9^2\big)^4 \cdot 7 &amp; \equiv (81)^4 \cdot 7 &amp; \=
pmod{10} \\
&amp;  \equiv 1^4 \cdot 7 &amp; \equiv 7 &amp; \pmod{10}. \ _\square \end{a=
rray}
\]
</p><!-- end-example --></blockquote>

<blockquote class=3D"example"><p>
Find the last three digits of \(2^{40}.\)</p>

<hr>

<p>We have</p>

<p>\[\begin{eqnarray*}2^{40} &amp;=3D&amp; \big(2^{10}\big)^4 \\ &amp;=3D&a=
mp; 1024^4 \\ &amp;\equiv&amp; 24^4 \\ &amp;\equiv&amp; 576^2 \pmod{1000}.\=
end{eqnarray*}\]</p>

<p>We can write \(576^2\) as </p>

<p>\[\begin{eqnarray*}(500+76)(500+76) &amp;=3D&amp; 250000+2\times500\time=
s 76+76\times76 \\ &amp;=3D&amp; 250000 + 76000 + 5776 \\ &amp;\equiv&amp; =
0 + 5776 \\ &amp;\equiv&amp; 776 \pmod{1000}.\end{eqnarray*}\]</p>

<p>Since \(2^{40}\) leaves a remainder of \(776\) when divided by \(1000\),=
 its last three digits are \(776\). \(_\square\)
</p><!-- end-example --></blockquote>

<p></p><div class=3D"problem-modal-container anchor" id=3D"problem-a-number=
-theory-problem-by-varun-rustagi">

    <div class=3D"wiki-problem" data-controller=3D"app/wiki:wikiShowProblem=
Answer" data-controller-inited=3D"true">

        <div class=3D"problem-container">
           =20

           =20
                <div class=3D"answer-container solv-details">
