swer</button>
                </div>
           =20

           =20
                <div class=3D"question-container">
   =20
        <p>What is the remainder when \(2^{123456789}\) is divided by 7?</p=
>

   =20
</div>
           =20

            <div class=3D"solution-container hide">
                <br><br>
                The correct answer is: <strong>1</strong>
               =20
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>
 <p></p>

<blockquote class=3D"example"><p>
Find an example of integers \(a, x, y, n, \) where \(x \equiv y \pmod{n}\),=
 but \(a^x \not \equiv a^y \pmod{n}\).</p>

<hr>

<p>Many combinations of \( a, x, y, n \) will work here. We present the cas=
e with  \(n =3D 3, a =3D2, x =3D 2\) and \(y =3D 5\), where we get \(2 \equ=
iv 5 \pmod{3}\), but \(2^2 \equiv 1 \pmod {3} \) while \(  2^5 \equiv 2\pmo=
d{3}\). \(_\square\)
</p><!-- end-example --></blockquote>

<p>The important takeaway is that the exponentiation property only works on=
 the base. If you want to work with the powers, you will need <a href=3D"ht=
tps://brilliant.org/wiki/eulers-theorem/" class=3D"wiki_link" title=3D" Eul=
er's theorem" target=3D"_blank"> Euler's theorem</a>.</p>

</div>
</div>

<div id=3D"division" class=3D"anchor skill-heading collapsed" data-controll=
er=3D"app/wiki:expandOrCollapse" data-controller-inited=3D"true">
    <header class=3D"section-header">
        <span class=3D"css-sprite-chevrons chevron"></span>
        <h2>Division</h2>

       =20
    </header>
</div>

<div class=3D"section collapsed" id=3D"section-division"><div class=3D"sect=
ion-container">

<p>This is tricky. Consider \( 4 \equiv 8 \pmod{4}\).  Note that we cannot =
simply divide both sides of the equation by 2, since \( 2 \not \equiv 4 \pm=
od{4}\). This shows that, in general, division is not well defined. As the =
following property shows, if we add the condition that \( k, N\) are coprim=
e, then division becomes well defined.</p>

<blockquote class=3D"theorem"><p>
<strong>Property of division in modular arithmetic</strong>:</p>

<p>If \( \gcd(k,N)=3D1\) and \( ka \equiv kb \pmod{N}\), then \( a \equiv b=
 \pmod{N}\).
</p><!-- end-theorem --></blockquote>

<p>This property is true because if \( k(a-b)\) is a multiple of \( N\) and=
 \( \gcd(k,N)=3D1\), then \( N\) must divide \( a-b\), or equivalently, \( =
a \equiv b \pmod{N}\).</p>

</div>
</div>

<div id=3D"modular-arithmetic-multiplicative-inverses" class=3D"anchor skil=
l-heading collapsed" data-controller=3D"app/wiki:expandOrCollapse" data-con=
troller-inited=3D"true">
    <header class=3D"section-header">
        <span class=3D"css-sprite-chevrons chevron"></span>
        <h2>Multiplicative Inverses</h2>

       =20
    </header>
</div>

<div class=3D"section collapsed" id=3D"section-modular-arithmetic-multiplic=
ative-inverses"><div class=3D"section-container">

<p>The modular inverse of \(a\) in the ring of integers modulo \(m\) is an =
integer \(x\) such that </p>

<p>\[ax \equiv 1 \pmod{m}.\]</p>

<p>From the <a href=3D"https://brilliant.org/wiki/euclidean-algorithm/" cla=
ss=3D"wiki_link" title=3D"Euclidean division algorithm" target=3D"_blank">E=
uclidean division algorithm</a> and <a href=3D"https://brilliant.org/wiki/b=
ezouts-identity/" class=3D"wiki_link" title=3D"B=C3=A9zout's identity" targ=
et=3D"_blank">B=C3=A9zout's identity</a>, we have the following result abou=
t the existence of multiplicative inverses in modular arithmetic:</p>

<blockquote class=3D"definition"><p>
If \( a\) and \(N\) are integers such that \( \gcd (a, N)=3D1\), then there=
 exists an integer \( x\) such that \( ax \equiv 1 \pmod{N}\). </p>

<p>\( x\) is called the <strong>multiplicative inverse</strong> of \( a\) m=
odulo \( N.\)
</p><!-- end-definition --></blockquote>

